                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d450">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">White</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-12-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 27, 1902</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. White reports that he has communicated the contents of Mr. Hay’s telegrams
                    of December 26 to Lord Lansdowne, who again expressed regret at the President’s
                    decision, but said that His Majesty’s Government gratefully take note of the
                    President’s kind offer to be of any further service possible.</p>
                <p>Lord Lansdowne says that Mr. Hay is at liberty to communicate to the Venezuelan
                    Government the propositions or reservations contained in the memorandum cabled
                    by Mr. White on December 23.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
